'''Kamisamuraizuka Kofun''' (上侍塚古墳) is a {{ill|zenpō-kōhō-fun|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=}} located in {{ill|Ōtawara|ja|大田原市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtawara|qq=}}, {{ill|Tochigi Prefecture|ja|栃木県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tochigi Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. Together with {{ill|Shimousamurai Kofun|lt=Shimousamurai Kofun|lt=Shimosamuraizuka Kofun|ja|下侍塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimosamuraizuka Kofun|qq=}}, it is part of the National Historic Site "Samuraizuka Kofun." This kofun is notable for being one of the first to undergo a scholarly excavation during the Edo period under the orders of {{ill|Tokugawa Mitsukuni|ja|徳川光圀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Mitsukuni|qq=}}, known as "Mito Kōmon."
== Overview == Kamisamuraizuka Kofun is a large zenpō-kōhō-fun constructed on the right bank of the {{ill|Naka River|ja|那珂川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naka River|qq=}}. Alongside Shimosamuraizuka Kofun, it represents one of the most significant ancient Kofuns in the Nasu region. Excavations date back to the 5th year of the Genroku era (1692), and further archaeological surveys were conducted starting in 2021.
The mound faces south, with a total length of 114 meters, making it the largest zenpō-kōhō-fun in the Nasu area and the second largest in Tochigi Prefecture after the {{ill|Fujimoto Kannonyama Kofun|ja|藤本観音山古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujimoto Kannonyama Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Ashikaga|ja|足利市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga|qq=}}.<ref name="OhtawaraCity">[https://www.city.ohtawara.tochigi.jp/docs/2013082767660/ Samuraizuka Kofun] (Ōtawara City website).</ref> The mound is covered with fukiishi (paving stones) and surrounded by a moat approximately 20 meters wide. The burial chamber is believed to have been constructed with clay.<ref name="descriptionboard">Site explanation board.</ref>
burial goods recovered during the Edo period include bronze mirrors, tubular beads, stone armlets, and iron objects such as armor fragments. These items were reburied in a wooden box following the excavation.<ref name="Asahi20230208">"Rediscovery Efforts for Edo built burial goods," ''Asahi Shimbun'' (February 8, 2023).</ref>
